Let’s talk about #lipedema 

I went back and forth on whether I would share my journey on here but I truly believe it’s so much more common than we know and if I can help other women get diagnosed then the vulnerability is worth it xx

Ever since I was 15 my legs have been trunk like and I’d always joke with my friends about my “cankles” and maybe you’ve noticed I tend to crop my photos at the knee 

Over the past 2 years my legs have become so heavy and tired, they bruise easily and the painful fat deposits do not go away no matter how much I exercise or diet. 

I can’t fully zip up ankle boots and knee high boots were never an option. Aesthetically it hurt me emotionally feeling like my legs didn’t match the rest of my body but physically the pain progressed quite a bit these past few years.

After spending HOURS online, I found @artlipo_lipedema_surgery and realized I had lipedema. After I got my diagnosis of stage 1 from my GP I started researching the lymph sparing lipo procedure which is currently the ONLY way of removing the lipedema fat. I’m booked in for May 30th to have the lipedema fat removed and am so excited and nervous and grateful I can have this done while I’m 31 before it progresses to stage 2. 

Lipedema affects 11% of women and most doctors don’t know the difference between lymphedema and lipedema. 

Canada unfortunately does not cover the surgery but many US insurance companies do. 

I’d recommend getting a referral to a specialist in your area and joining lipedema support groups on Facebook for sooo much info on getting a diagnosis in your area.

Some photos and notes from my #lipedemasurgery and recovery 🤠some photos show blood so don’t swipe if you don’t like ! Reminder that lipedema is a condition where you have painful fat deposits that cannot be dieted or exercised away. I was stage 1 of 3 at the time of my surgery. 

I had my surgery may 30th with Dr. Su at @artlipo_lipedema_surgery he did my lowers, knees 360 and inner thighs. 

I arrived at 6:30 AM with Ryan and my nurse brought me back and weighed me, took my blood pressure and went over my medical history. She then washed me down and had me change into a black bra and underwear and gave me a Percocet , anti nausea pill and antibiotic. She took photos of my legs and then I waited for Dr.Su.

He drew on my legs where he planned to work and give me an idea of what I could expect and then began giving me lidocaine numbing which felt like bee stings. 

Once I was numb he made small incisions and did tumescent numbing under the skin. This was the most painful part for me. It’s like strong vibrations and hurts where the fat is most fibrotic. The procedure itself I couldn’t feel but I was constantly changing positions and flexing so he could get the best results. Halfway through I stood up and he checked the results and decided to do more on the inner thigh. After surgery I was washed up, put into tinnnny compression, bandaged and hopped into an Uber to the hotel with Ryan.

I ended up fainting that evening because I didn’t eat enough and wasn’t able to keep the painkillers down. The next day I had my post op visit where my compression was changed and dr. Su examined my legs. We flew home that evening and it was the worst 8 hours of my life but I’d do it all again for these results. 

Recovery was harder than I anticipated because I wasn’t taking painkillers. I changed compression daily after showering and tried to walk a bit each day. By week 2 I was walking a few hours a day and by week 3 I am driving! The bruising and swelling aren’t settled yet but the lightness and lack of pain in my legs already has been incredible to feel!!! If you have more questions leave a comment and I’ll try to answer xxx
